REPORT

Registrar-General's Office,

Melbourne, 5th October, 1863.

SIR,

I have the honor to submit the "Religions of the People," forming the fourth part of the returns complied from the Census taken on the 7th April, 1861. [Religions of the People.]

2.

A general summary of this part, together with summaries of the "Occupations," "Birthplaces," and " Ages" of the People, was published in theGovernment Gazetteabout twelve months after the Census was taken ; and the same summary appeared subsequently in the "Statistics of Victoria" for the year 1861. [General Summary previously published.]

3.

Although the tables, with the exception of the General-Summary, are now published for the first time, detailed particulars respecting the statistics of the various religions in different localities have, upon application, in numerous instances been furnished direct from this department to the heads of denominations and other persons seeking the information. [Information respecting religions furnished when applied for.]

4.

The following tables are now presented :— [Summary of contents of the tables.]

  1. —The number of persons belonging to each of the principal sects at the various census periods since 1841, and the increase of each sect during the intervals between the Censuses.

  2. —The number of persons of both sexes of different religious denominations, living in Victoria at the three last Censuses, and the numerical and proportionate increase or diminution of each denomination during the intervals between the Censuses.

  3. —The numbers and proportions per cent. of persons of different religions at the successive Census periods since 1841.

  4. —The number of persons of both sexes of different religions living in Victoria at the three last Censuses, and the proportions per cent. of those belonging to each sect to the total population at each of those periods.

  5. —The number of persons of both sexes living in Victoria, in the municipalities, and in the mining districts, and the proportions per cent. of those belonging to each sect to the specified totals.

  6. —The subdivisions of the "Free Presbyterians," "Other Presbyterians," "Other Wesleyan Methodists," and "Other Persuasions;" being a summary of the minor sects returned in the Census.

  7. —The religions of persons of both sexes living in each county and pastoral district.

  8. —The religions of persons of both sexes living in each electoral province.

  9. —The religions of persons of both sexes living in each electoral district.

  10. —The religions of persons of both sexes living in each corporate town and municipality.

  11. —The religions of persons of both sexes living on the gold fields in each mining district.

  12. —The religions of persons of both sexes living in the parishes, townships, and principal places situated within each county and pastoral district.

5.

The total number of persons enumerated on the 7th April, 1861, was 540,322. From 522,392 of this number returns of their religious belief were obtained, but the schedules were silent as to the religions of the remaining 17,930 individuals. [Number of persons from whom returns of religion was received.]

6.

Embodying all the sects professing Protestantism, the number according to the Census Returns claiming to be Protestants amounted in the aggregate to 381,113, or about seven-tenths of the population. The Catholics, including Roman Catholics and those returned as "Catholics" simply, numbered 109,829 or about a fifth of the inhabitants of the colony. The Jews numbered 2,903 or one in every 186 living, and the residue, embracing all other sects, those of no religion, and those whose religions were not specified, to 46,477, or rather less than a twelfth of the population. [Number of Protestants, Catholics, Jews, and residue.]

7.

The proportions in every thousand of the population of each of these divisions were as follow :— [Proportions of Protestants, Catholics, and Jews to the population.]

Number in every 1000 of the Inhabitants of the Colony.
Protestants705.3
Catholics203.2
Jews5.4
Residue86.1
1000.0

8.

All these bodies were found to have increased considerably since the previous Census. The Protestants augmented by 83,934, which was equivalent to 282 being added to every thousand of their numbers in 1857 ; thence Catholics increased by 32,478, or an addition of 420 to every thousand of their previous number ; the Jews by 695, or 315 in every thousand ; and the residue by 12,449, or 366 in every thousand. The total population during the same period received an addition of 315 to every thousand of its numbers, thereby showing a relative increase much greater than that of the Protestants, not nearly so great as that of the Catholics, and exactly equal to that of the Jews. [Increase since previous Census of Protestants, Catholics, and Jews.]

9.

The most prominent bodies amongst the Protestants are members of the Church of England, Presbyterians, and Wesleyans. According to the Census Returns the first of these numbered 212,068, or 39 per cent. of the population ; the second 87,103, or 16 per cent. ; and the third 46,511, or 8[formula]; per cent. The increase of the first since 1857 was at the rate of 21 per cent., that of the second was at the rate of 32 per cent., and that of the third was at the rate of 64 per cent. Besides these, the aggregate of the other Protestant sects amounted to 35,431 or 6½ per cent. of the population ; their increase since 1857 being at the rate of 29 per cent. [Numbers and increase of members of the Church of England, and of the Presbyterian and Wesleyan Churches.]

10.

All these sects admit of being still further subdivided. Under the general heading "Church of England" besides the numbers actually returned as belonging to it are classed 454 members of the Free Church of England and 5,919 persons merely set down as "Protestants." The latter have always, in previous Censuses, been classified as members of the Church of England, as it was found upon enquiry that persons attached to other Protestant denominations usually distinguished with great precision the particular sect to which they belonged, and those simply returning themselves as "Protestants" did so under the impression that from the use of that term without qualification they would naturally be considered as belonging to the Church of England. [Subdivisions of Church of England.]

11.

Under the heading of Presbyterians are comprised, besides 6,835 returning themselves as such, without indicating to which branch of the Presbyterian body they adhered, the Presbyterian Church of Victoria possessing 5,052 members, the Church of Scotland with 36,917, the United Presbyterian Church with 16,734, the Free Church of Scotland and Free Presbyterian Church with 21,219, and other Presbyterian Churches with 346. [Subdivision of the Presbyterian body.]

12.

The two last of these divisions of the Presbyterian Church consist of several distinct bodies, which it was found necessary to distinguish after the other returns had been completed. It was then ascertained that, besides 1,811 Free Presbyterians, undefined, the Free Presbyterian Church included the Free Presbyterian Church of Scotland with 19,297 adherents, the Free Presbyterian Church of Scotland in Victoria with 65, the Free Presbyterian Church of Victoria with 27, the United Free Presbyterian Church with 10, the Gaelic Church with 6, the Independent Scotch Church with 2, and Chalmers' Church with 1 member. It was also found that the "Other Presbyterian Churches" comprised the Evangelical Union of Scotland with 17 members, the Reformed Presbyterian Church with 149, persons returning themselves merely as Scotch Presbyterians numbering 116, and those returning themselves as Covenanters or as belonging to the Secession or Relief Churches, &c., numbering 64. [Minor Presbyterian sects classed as Free Presbyterians.] [Minor sects classed as "Other Presbyterians."]

13.

The Wesleyan Methodists comprise those returned as Wesleyans, Wesleyan Methodists, or Methodists, numbering 40,799, Primitive Methodists numbering 3,775, members of the Wesleyan Methodist Association numbering 1,146, Bible Christians numbering 651, and other Wesleyan Methodists numbering 140. The latter may be still further subdivided into 11 Independent Methodists, 15 New Connection Methodists, 12 members of the Wesleyan Free Church, 56 United Methodist, and 46 Episcopalian Methodists, Wesleyan Reformers, Ranters, &c. [Subdivisions of the Wesleyan body.]

14.

Amongst the other Protestant sects or those not included in the three principal bodies, viz., the Church of England, the Presbyterians, and the Wesleyans, are found 12,777 Independents or Congregationalists, 9,001 Baptists, 10,043 Lutherans and German Protestants, 1,430 Unitarians, 273 members of the Society of Friends, 650 Calvinists and Calvinistic Methodists, and 1,257 of other Persuasions. [Independents, Baptists, Lutherans, Society of Friends, Calvinists, &c.]

15.

An attempt has been made to trace the exact manner in which those who, in the first instance, were tabulated as of "Other Persuasions" actually returned themselves, which elicited the following particulars :—144 claimed to belong to the Catholic and Apostolic Church, 95 were set down merely as Dissenters, 7 were of the Dutch Reformed Church, 31 called themselves Evangelists, 7 were Glassites, 5 Huguenots, 52 Moravians, 9 Morrisonians, 23 Nonconformists, 441 Plymouth Brethren, Disciples of Christ, or Christians, 7 Primitive Christians, 22 Reformers, 12 Separatists, 5 Spiritualists, 198 Swedenborgians, 98 Universalists, 8 Welsh Protestants, and 93 belonging to other sects. [Minor sects classed as of "Other Persuassions."]

16.

The Catholics, as returned in the Census, are only divisible into Roman Catholics numbering 107,610, and Catholics not otherwise defined amounting to 2,219. [Roman Catholics, and Catholics not otherwise defined.]

17.

The Jews, as has been already stated, amounted to 2,903. This number admits of no subdivision. [Jews.]

18.

The residue consists of 239 belonging to the Greek Church, 395 Israelites, 108 Latter-Day Saints or Mormons, 952 styling themselves as Unsectarian, of No Denomination, or Secularists, 441 of no Religion, 189 Mahomedans, 1,672 Pagans (not Chinese), 24,551 Chinese not professing Christianity, and 17,930 of Religion unspecified. [Greek Church, Israelites, Mormons, No Denomination, No Religion, Mahomedans, Pagans, &c.]

19.

With reference to the latter, it will be remembered that it was stated in the report which prefaced the first part of the Census Returns, that this Census differed from previous ones in the Colony, inasmuch as the return of religious belief was for the first time not made compulsory, but persons having conscientious scruples about stating their religion might omit to do so, and insert the word "object" instead. To this provision [Objecting to state their religion from conscientious scruples.]

May be attributed the large number of persons of unknown religions appearing in these returns. The total number of persons who availed themselves of it was 11,536, and these were, therefore, set down as "Objecting to state their religion on conscientious grounds." The remainder of the unspecified were so in consequence of the schedules being defectively filled up, and amounted to 6,394, of which 2,391 were known to be adults, and 642 to be children.

20.

What sect the persons who objected to state their religion principally belonged to it is difficult to determine. It appears that the Independents or Congregationalists, as a rule, have a dislike to comply with any State demand as to matters connected with their religion, and it has, therefore, been supposed that these objectors belonged for the most part of them. But this theory is hardly tenable in face of the fact that 12,777 persons voluntarily returned themselves as Congregationalists, and this denomination showed an increase of 19 per cent. upon its numbers at the previous Census. [Claims of the Congregationalists to add the objectors to their numbers considered.]

21.

There seems, therefore, to be no good ground for believing that the Congregationalists alone can lay claim to add the objectors to their returned numbers. It is well known that many persons in other sects look upon enquiries respecting their religion as inquisitorial, and, consequently, refuse to comply with them, if not absolutely compelled to do so. It is also possible that in some instances persons who had secretly changed their religion, and who wished to conceal the fact from those with whom they were living, may have been among the number. [Reasons for objecting to give returns of religion.]

22.

In all the denominations the number of males was larger than that of females. The Church of England was the one in which the relative proportion of the sexes approached nearest to that of the total population, there being in that body 66 females, and in the whole colony, 65 females to every 100 males. The Roman Catholic Church was the one whose members showed the least disparity as regards the sexes, the proportion being 84 females to 100 males. The Wesleyans stood next with 82 females to 100 males ; the Independents next, with 81 ; then the Baptists with 80, the Presbyterians with 71, the Jews with 56. Those objecting to state their religion from conscientious scruples were in the proportion of 52 females to 100 males ; and the residue, excluding all the bodies named, showed 13 females to 100 males. Of this residue it is worthy to note that the Mormons, who from their alleged tenets might be supposed to have an excess of females over males, have but 18 of the former to 90 of the latter, or a proportion of only 20 females to 100 males. [Proportion of the sexes in the different denominations.]

23.

All the Protestant sects combined showed a proportion of 68 females to every 100 males. The Catholics, including Roman Catholics and Catholics not otherwise defined, showed 84 females to 100 males. The remainder of the population not included in Protestant or Catholic bodies, showed 17 females to 100 males, if the Chinese be included, and without the Chinese it showed 40 females to every 100 males. [Number of females to every 100 males in Protestant and Catholic bodies.]

24.

The number of Chinese professing Christianity was 181, out of a total of 24,732, or about 1 in 137. Of these 153 were set down simply as "Christians," without any particular sect being named ; 21 were returned as members of the Church of England, 1 as a Baptist, 5 as Roman Catholics, and 1 as a Catholic undefined. [Chinese professing Christianity.]

25.

Of 12 Aborigines who professed to be Christians 8 were returned as belonging to the Church of England, 3 as Wesleyans, and 1 as an Independent. The total number of Aborigines was 1,694. Those who had embraced Christianity were therefore in the proportion of 1 to 141. [Aborigines professing Christianity.]

26.

Dividing the inhabitants of the colony into the urban population, or that contained in corporate towns and municipalities, and the extra-municipal or rural population, it will readily be believed that some religions preponderate in the former and some in the latter. Protestants, with the exception of the Presbyterians, seem to flourish most in towns, as also do the Jews and the persons objecting to state [Religion of the urban and extra urban population.]

their religion from conscientious scruples ; but the Presbyterians, the Roman Catholics, and the residue, consisting of Israelites, Mormons, Mahomedans, Pagans, persons of no denomination, or of no religion, were more numerous in the rural districts, as will be seen by the following figures, from which, it must be premised, those altogether unspecified in the schedules are excluded :—

27.

Taking the gold fields, part of which are included in the town and part in the country districts, it is found that the members of the Church of England, the Presbyterians, the Roman Catholics, and the Jews, were less numerous in proportion to their population than the same bodies were in proportion to the population of the whole colony ; but that the Wesleyans, and the residue, exclusive of the unspecified, were relatively more numerous on the gold fields ; whilst the "Other Protestants" and those objecting to state their religions bore about the same relation to the population of the gold fields that they did to that of the colony. The following is the per centage :— [Religions of the gold-field population.]

28.

To complete the Statistics relating to the "Religions of the People," it becomes necessary to find out the amount of provision made by each denomination for the

religious wants of its adherents at the time the Census was taken. An approximation to this information has been obtained from various sources, and is given in the following table :—

[* This includes not only Churches and Chaples, but Schoolhouses and other buildings, both public and private, in which Divine Service is held.]

29.

It thus appears that of the four largest bodies, viz., the Church of England, the Presbyterians, the Wesleyans, and the Roman Catholics, those with the fewest clergymen in proportion to their number were the Church of England and the Roman Catholics, there being in the former only one clergyman to every 2,613 members, and in the latter one to every 2,615 members. The Presbyterians had of clergy more than double these numbers in proportion to their strength, or one to every 1,049 souls ; and the Wesleyans were still more amply provided, having one clergyman to every 694 souls. With reference to the numbers of clergymen in these and the minor denominations, as given in the table, it is right to state that some of the sects possess also officials who, without being regularly ordained, perform the functions of clergymen, either wholly or partially, such as lay readers, local preachers, mission agents, &c. ; and therefore in these sects the number of religious instructors, in proportion to their total numbers, was larger than appears by the table.

30.

With respect to church accommodation, the following facts are gathered from the table. The places of worship belonging to the Church of England could only hold

16 per cent. of their numbers at one time, whilst those of the Roman Catholics could contain 27 per cent., and those of the Presbyterians 35 per cent. The Wesleyans had room in their religious edifices for 49,533 persons, whilst their returned numbers only amounted to 46,511, or 3,022 less. The independents and Baptists had room respectively for 85 and 84 per cent. of their numbers, the Society of Friends for 55 per cent., and the Jews for 74 per cent. The "Other Protestants," in which most of the minor sects are embodied, had accommodation for 87 per cent. more than their returned numbers, and this renders it probable that many of the persons objecting to state their religion from conscientious scruples may adhere to some of those sects. The Israelites or Wroeites had place for more than double their numbers, a provision which is perhaps rendered necessary by the attendance at their religious services of persons not members of their Church.

31.

In conclusion, I feel it only due to the officers in my department to remark that much pains have been bestowed in the preparation of this return so as to make it as reliable a statement of the various religions existing in the colony as it is possible to obtain. The gentlemen employed upon its preparation received the strictest injunctions to place all persons exactly according to the religions they stated themselves to be of in the schedules, and this instruction I have every reason to believe was faithfully fulfilled. Doubtful entries were carefully weighed, and if after due reference and examination doubt was still found to exist they were tabulated in the unspecified column.

32.

I trust that the Return as presented will be found of value to the heads and leading members of the different religious bodies as well as to the public at large.

I have the honor to be,

Sir,

Your most obedient servant,

WILLIAM HENRY ARCHER,

Registrar-General.

The Honorable the Chief Secretary,

Melbourne.

The number of Chinese professing to be Christians was 181 ; of whom 21 were returned as members of the Church of England, I as a Baptist, 5 as Roman Catholics, and 1 as a Catholic undefined ; the remainder (153) being simply set down as Christians. Of the Aborigines 8 were set down as belonging to the Church of England, 3 as Wesleyans, and 1 as an Independent.

REPORT.

Registrar General's Office,

Melbourne, 13th May, 1864.

SIR,

I have the honor to submit the "Ages of the People," being Part V. of the returns compiled from the Census taken on the 7th April, 1861. [Ages of the People.]

2.

The following is a brief statement of the contents of the various tables :— [Summary of Contents Tables.]

  1. The number of persons, males and females, in the colony of Victoria, at, above, and below, each year of age.

  2. The increase of persons of both sexes, males and females, at different ages in the intervals between the various Censuses.

  3. The proportions per cent. of the persons, males and females, at each age period to the total of all ages at the last six Censuses.

  4. The proportions of males and females in every 100 of the population at each age period, as returned at the last six Censuses.

  5. The proportions per cent. of the persons, males and females, at each quinquennial period of age to the total of all ages at the last three Censuses.

  6. The proportions of males and females in every 100 of the population at each quinquennial period of age at the three last Censuses.

  7. The numbers and proportions per cent. of persons, males and females, inclusive and exclusive of Chinese and Aborigines, at each quinquennial period of age ; also the numbers of Chinese and Aborigines at each age period.

  8. The ages, in quinquennial periods, of persons, males and females, living in the colony, in corporate towns and municipalities, and on the gold-fields ; and the proportions per cent. of the numbers at each age to the total at all ages.

  9. The ages, in decennial periods, of persons, males and females, living in the colony, in corporate towns and municipalities, and on the gold fields, and the proportions per cent. of the numbers at each age to the total at all ages.

  10. The ages in vicennial periods, of persons, males and females, living in the colony, in corporate towns and municipalities, and on the gold fields, and the proportions per cent. of the numbers at each age to the total at all ages.

  11. The proportions of males and females in every 100 of the population at each quinquennial age period in the colony, in corporate towns and municipalities, and on the gold fields.

  12. The ages of persons, males and females, living in each county and pastoral district.

  13. The ages of persons, males and females, in each electoral province.

  14. The ages of persons, males and females, in each electoral district.

  15. The ages of persons, males and females, living in each municipality.

  16. The ages of persons, males and females, living on the gold fields in each mining district.

  17. The ages of males and females, in the parishes, townships, and principal places in each county and pastoral district.

3.

The exact ages of 323,863 males and 211,000 females, or of 534,863 persons in all, were returned upon the Census schedules. Of the residue there was evidence to [Number of persons respecting whose returns of age were received.]

Determine that 3,824 males and 453 females were adults, and that 140 males and 105 females were children ; but nothing was recorded whereby the ages or periods of life of the remaining 824 males and 113 females could be ascertained.

4.

In compiling these returns the units of population were tabulated for each year of age up to 15, after which they were grouped in periods of five years. The numbers between 20 and 21 were also ascertained, in order that, by adding them to those under 20, it might be possible to determine what section of the population had attained its legal majority. In addition to these groupings the exact ages of all persons over 80 were recorded. [Groupings used in compiling the returns.]

5.

To arrive, however, at the probable numbers at each year of age Table I. was compiled. In constructing this table, the actual numbers were taken for each year from infancy up to the age of 15 ; also from 20 to 21 years, and for each year beyond 80. The ages between the quinquennial periods, in which the remainder of the population were grouped, were then calculated by proportion, and the unspecified were distributed over the whole in the same ratio as those actually enumerated. [Probable numbers at each year of age.]

6.

Numerous interesting results may be derived from this table. It appears that of both sexes, those at and above 25, and those at and under 26, are nearly equal, whence it follows that the total population divides itself into two equal parts between the ages of 25 and 26. By the same means it is seen that the male population divides itself into two equal parts at the period between 27 and 28 years of age, and the female population halves itself at the period between 20 and 21 years. [Ages at which the population divides itself into two equal parts.]

7.

In like manner the population may be divided at any given age, and the numbers above and below that age may be found at a glance. The numbers under and over 21 are thus seen to have been— [Numbers under and over 21 years of age.]

Males under 21106,871over 21221,777
Females under 21105,640over 21106,031
Both Sexes under 21212,514over 21327,808

8.

Hence it results that of every thousand males living at the time the Census was taken 675 were of full age and 325 were under age ; of every thousand females 501 were of full age and 499 were under age ; and of every thousand of both sexes 607 were of full age and 393 were under age. [Proportion of the population of full age and under age.]

9.

The persons over 80 numbered 298, of whom those who had reached to 85 and upwards amounted to 55. Those who had passed their ninetieth birthday numbered only 23 ; but 14 had passed their ninety-fifth ; and no more than 4 had passed their hundred. [Number of persons over 80 years of age.]

10.

The oldest persons returned were—a male aged 110, another male aged 108, a female aged 103, a male aged 100, and a female aged 99. Also four males aged 97, two males and a female aged 96, and one male and one female aged 95. In assuming ages for the unspecified and distributing them amongst those whose ages were actually returned, no change was made in the numbers at any age over 85. These, therefore, appear in the table exactly as they were extracted from the householders' schedules. [Ages of the oldest persons returned.]

11.

Tables II., III., and IV. Give the principal figures from the age-tables at the last six Censuses, and as until the census of 1854 the ages were only classified under seven heads or periods, those returned in the later censuses have been similarly grouped in these tables for the sake of uniformity. The Chinese and Aborigines have also been omitted, because until 1857 there were few or no Chinese in the Colony, and the Aborigines were not enumerated. [Tables showing ages at last six Censuses.]

12.

The per centage of the numbers at each age-period to the total of all ages is given in Table V. for the last three Censuses. By omitting the decimal points in this table, the numbers in every 10,000 of the population are obtained, and by adding the numbers at several quinquenniads the proportions at any period of life may be compared. Thus, by adding the first three periods, it is seen that, in 1861, 3,494 persons in every 10,000 living were under 15 years of age, against 3,009 in 1857 and 2,711 in 1854 ; by adding the next ten periods it is made apparent that 6,447 persons in 10,000 were between 15 and 65 in 1861, against 6,943 in 1857, and against 7,249 in 1854 ; and by taking the sum of the last five periods, those upwards of 65 are seen to have amounted to 59 in 10,000 in [Numbers of children, adults, and old people at last three Censuses.]

1861, to 48 in 1857, and to 40 in 1854. Whereby it is proved that the children and old people in our population are increasing faster than are persons in the prime of life.

13.

The publication of the Census returns of New South Wales and South Australia enables a comparison to be made between the physical strength of our population and that of those colonies. The following figures show that the population of Victoria has only 3,553 persons under 15 and over 65 in 10,000 of all ages, against 3,928 in New South Wales and 4,453 in South Australia ; thereby showing for Victoria a smaller ratio of the physically dependent classes than for either of the adjacent colonies, and this notwithstanding the Chinese are eliminated from out calculation. The Chinese were enumerated at 24,732, and were nearly all adult males. These, if included, would therefore add considerably to the numerical estimate of the strength of the effective classes of our community. [Physical strength of the population in Victoria, New South Wales, and South Australia.]

Victoria.N. S. Wales.South Australia.
Under 153,4943,7974,374
15 to 656,4476,0725,547
65 and upwards5913179
10,00010,00010,000

14.

It has been assumed in the Mother Country, that the population under 10 years of age and over 70 are sustained by the exertions of those between 20 and 60, whilst persons between the ages of 10 and 20 and between 60 and 70, as a rule, support themselves, but are not able to contribute to the sustenance of others. By a calculation, based upon this supposition, it was found that at the Census of the United Kingdom taken in 1851, the persons at the supporting period of life were charged with the sustenance of a class amounting to 57 per cent. of their own numbers. When the Census of Victoria was taken in 1854, the aged and the young amounted only to 32 per cent. of those at the middle period of life ; in 1857 the former had increased to 38 per cent. of the latter, and in 1861 to 50 per cent., thus showing at each successive Census a nearer approach in this respect to the standard of Great Britain. [Dependent and supporting classes in Victoria and Great Britain compared.]

15.

If the persons under 20 and over 60 are considered as the dependent classes, a wide difference is found to exist between Great Britain and Victoria, as will be seen by the following figures :— [Young, middle-aged, and old, in Great Britain and Victoria.]

Great Britain.Victoria.
1851.1861.
Numbers under 20 and over 60 in every 1,000 living523426
Numbers between 20 and 60 in every 1,000 living477574

16.

The ages of males and females in Great Britain and Victoria are compared in the following table, by which it is seen that the males between 20 and 40, or at what is commonly termed the soldiers' age, are only 307 in every 1,000 of all ages in the former, against 487 in every 1,000 in the latter, and that the females from infancy to 40 years of age, or at and below the fruitful or child-bearing period, are as 753 in Great Britain to 889 in Victoria. [Ages of males and females in Great Britain and Victoria compared.]

TABLE SHOWING COMPARISON OF AGES OF MALES AND FEMALES IN GREAT BRITAIN AND VICTORIA.

1,0001,0009991,000

17.

By Table VI. the proportions of males and females, at each quinquennial period, may be ascertained for the last three Censuses. It will be found on reference to this table that the proportions differ considerably at the different ages, but that the only periods at which the females exceed the males are between the ages of 5 and 10, at which in every 1,000 of both sexes there are 503 females to 497 males, and between 15 and 20, when there are 512 females to 488 males. The periods when the greatest disparity between the sexes exists are 40 to 50, and upwards of 80, the former showing only 309 and the latter only 307 females in every 1,000 of both sexes. [Proportions of the sexes at the various age periods.]

18.

The ages of the Chinese and Aborigines are given in Table VII., as far as they were returned in the Census schedules. It appears that as regards the Chinese males the ages of 22,145, out of 24,724, were specified, as also were the ages of the eight Chinese females who were in the Colony on the Census night. The males were, as may be supposed, nearly all adults, those under 15 amounting only to 110, and those under 20 to 1,158. A few of them, however, appear to have arrived at advanced ages, inasmuch as no less than 28 were returned as being upwards of 70, and 6 as being upwards of 80 years old. The Chinese females were returned as follows :—1 between 10 and 15, 2 between 20 and 25, 3 between 25 and 30, and 2 between 30 and 35. [Ages of Chinese.]

19.

The exact ages of only 613 Aborigines, out of 1,694, were ascertained. Of the residue, however, 759 were set down as adults and 128 as children. Adding the latter to those whose returned ages were under 15, and the former to those over that age, we have 224 children to 1,271 adults, or only about 150 children in 1,000 of all ages ; a result showing a marked contrast with the population of European extraction, in which there are 349 children under 15 in 1,000 of all ages. The oldest Aborigines returned were—1 female between 75 and 80, 3 males between 70 and 75, and 1 male between 65 and 70. [Ages of Aborigines.]

20.

The next four tables (VIII., IX., X., and XI.) refer to the population living in municipalities and on the gold fields, as well as to that of the colony at large, and give the ages in quinquennial, decennial, and vicennial periods ; also the proportions of those at each period to the total at all ages, and the proportions of males and females at each period. The ages of the extra-urban, or country population, may be found by subtracting the numbers of the municipal population at each age from those of the inhabitants of the entire colony. The ages in these sections will be found to present diversities, as also will those on the gold fields, which are situated part in the municipal and part in the country districts. These may be traced in the following table, which gives the numbers at each vicennial period, in every 10,000, living in the entire colony and in each of the divisions named :— [Ages in municipalities in country districts and on gold fields.]

TABLE SHOWING THE COMPARATIVE AGES OF THE MUNICIPAL, EXTRA-MUNICIPAL AND MINING POPULATIONS.

10,00010,00010,00010,000

21.

It will be observed that the young and the old, or those under 20 and over 60, are, in proportion to the population, more numerous in the towns than in either the country or the mining districts ; that the middle-aged, or those between 40 and 60, are more numerous in the country districts ; and that those between 20 and 40 are proportionally the strongest on the gold fields. [Comparative ages of the urban, extra-urban, and mining population.]

22.

The mean age of the people of Victoria is about 23 years and 7 months, that of the males about 25 years and 5 months, and that of the females 20 years and nearly 6 months. The average age of males, therefore, exceeds that of females by about five years. In England the mean age of males is 25.96 years, and therefore does not differ much from that in Victoria ; but that of females in widely different, being 10 months in excess of that of males. [Mean age of the population.]

23.

The following table shows the average age of the people of Victoria at the last six Censuses. It will be observed, that since 1854 the average age of the population of both sexes has gradually become reduced. [Average age of the population at each Census period.]

24.

Table XII. Gives the number of males and females at each age in the proclaimed counties and unsettled districts, and Tables XIII. to XVI. Give the number at each age in the parliamentary, municipal, and mining divisions of the colony. Table XVII. Embraces each town, township, parish, goldworking, or other subdivisions throughout the colony. The copious index to this Table will be found greatly to facilitate its use.

I trust that these remarks will be found to afford sufficient information respecting the returns published herewith.

I have the honor to be,

Sir,

Your most obedient Servant,

WILLIAM HENRY ARCHER,

The Honorable the Chief Secretary,

CONJUGAL CONDITION OF THE PEOPLE.

POPULATION ENUMERATED 7TH APRIL, 1861.

PRESENTED TO BOTH HOUSES OF PARLIAMENT BY HIS EXCELLENCYS COMMAND.

BY AUTHORITY:

JOHN FERRES, GOVERNMENT PRINTER, MELBOURNE.

REPORT.

Registrar-General's Office,

Melbourne, 24th August, 1864.

SIR,

I have the honor to submit the returns of the Conjugal Condition of the People of Victoria, as compiled from the Census schedules collected on the 7th April, 1861. [Conjugal Condition of the People.]

2.

With reference to the long period which has intervened between the taking of the Census and the publication of these detailed returns, I think it right to remind you that the delay has not occurred in this department. The returns of the eight parts of the Census were ready for the press, so far as this department is connected, before the end of 1862. [Delay in publishing Census returns.]

3.

General summaries of all the parts of the Census have, however, appeared in the Blue Books for 1861 and 1862 ; and the more detailed returns of this and the other unprinted parts have been lying since their completion in the statistic branch of this office, where they have been made available for general reference, for which I have deemed it my duty to afford every possible facility. [General Summaries already published.]

4.

The following is brief statement of the contents of the various tables herewith presented :— [Summary of contents of tables.]

  1. The proportions of married and single in every 100 persons, males and females, of all ages, living in Victoria at the last six Census periods.

  2. The numbers of unmarried, distinguishing the males under and over 20, and the females under and over 15 ; the number of husbands and wives, widowers and widows, of all ages, with the proportions per cent. of the unmarried, married, and widowed of either sex to their respective totals at the last three Censuses.

  3. The number of males and females unmarried, married, and widowed, in 1861 at quinquennial periods of age ; and the proportion per cent. of those in each condition to the total of each age period living at the last two Censuses.

  4. The number of bachelors of 20 years old and upwards, and the number of spinsters of 15 years old and upwards, the excess of the former over the latter, and the number of bachelors to every 100 spinsters in each county and district, and in the entire Colony at the three last Censuses.

  5. The number of husbands and wives, the excess of the former over the latter, or the contrary ; and the number of husbands to every 100 wives in each county and pastoral district, and in the entire Colony at the three last Censuses.

  6. The number of males and females, married, unmarried, and widowed, at each quinquennial period of age, and the proportions per cent. of those in each condition to the total living at each age period.

  7. The number of males and females, married, unmarried, and widowed, at decennial periods of age, and the proportion per cent. of those in each condition to the total living at each age period.

  8. The number of males and females, married, unmarried, and widowed, at vicennial periods of age, and the proportion per cent. of those in each condition to the total living at each age period.

  9. The number of males and females unmarried, married, and widowed, at each quinquennial age period, living in the Colony, in the municipalities, and on the gold fields.

  10. The proportion of married, unmarried, and widowed, in every 100 males and females living in the Colony, in the municipalities, and on the gold fields, at each quinquennial age period.

  11. The number of unmarried, married, and widowed, of either sex, of all ages, and of 20 years old and upwards, in each county and pastoral district.

  12. The number of unmarried, married, and widowed, of either sex, of all ages, and of 21 years old and upwards, in each electoral district.

  13. The numbers and ages of the unmarried, married, widowed, and unspecified, as to condition of both sexes, in each county and pastoral district.

  14. The numbers and ages of the unmarried, married, widowed, and unspecified, as to condition of both sexes, in each electoral province.

  15. The numbers and ages of the unmarried, married, widowed, and unspecified, as to condition, in each electoral district.

  16. The numbers and ages of the unmarried, married, widowed, and unspecified, as to condition, in each corporate town and municipality.

  17. The numbers and ages of the unmarried, married, widowed, and unspecified, as to condition, living on the gold fields in each mining district.

5.

In compiling the returns of the Conjugal Condition of the People, it was found necessary, for many reasons, to exclude from the tables all mention of the Chinese and Aborigines ; the migratory population, respecting whom no particulars, except the numbers of either sex, were known, were also omitted. By these eliminations, the numbers of the population are brought down to 300,005 males and 210,547 females, making a total of 510,552, instead of the whole number enumerated (540,322), which has been dealt with in the first five parts of the Census returns. [Chinese, Aborigines, and travellers omitted from present returns.]

6.

This population, counting all ages from infancy upwards, consisted of 202,384 unmarried males and 119,108 unmarried females ; of 88,840 husbands and 84,550 wives ; of 6,834 widowers and 6,623 widows ; besides 1,947 adult males and 266 adult females of whom the return of conjugal condition was either stated ambiguously or altogether omitted from the schedules. [Numbers of married, unmarried, and widowed.]

7.

The number of husbands returned exceeded the wives by 4,290, proving that the married men who have come to Victoria, attracted by the fame of our gold fields and by other causes, have exceeded by 4,290 those who, leaving their wives behind them, have gone from the Colony to seek their fortunes elsewhere. [Excess of husbands over wives.]

8.

There were more wives than husbands in Anglesey, Bourke, Follett, Grant, and Normanby ; in all the other counties, and in all the unsettled districts, there were more husbands than wives. [Counties in which wives exceeded husbands.]

9.

The number of married couples who slept in the same house, and also the number who were separated from each other on the Census night, have been ascertained from the schedules, and the result is shown in the following Table :—

TABLE SHOWING THE TOTAL NUMBER OF HUSBANDS AND THE TOTAL NUMBER OF WIVES, THE NUMBER OF HUSBANDS WHOSE WIVES WERE ABSENT, OF WIVES WHOSE HUSBANDS WERE ABSENT, AND OF HUSBANDS AND WIVES WHO WERE LIVING TOGETHER ON THE CENSUS NIGHT ; ALSO, THE PROPORTIONS PER CENT.
Total Number of Husbands.Total Number of Wives.Number of Husbands whose Wives were absent.Number of Wives whose Husbands were absent.Number of Husbands and Wives living together.Proportion per Cent.
Of Husbands whose Wives were absent.Of Husbands living with their Wives.Of Wives whose Husbands were absent.Of Wives living with their Husbands.
88,84084,55013,1698,87975,67114.8285.1810.5089.50

10.

It thus appears that 75,671 husbands and 75,671 wives slept in the same houses ; that 13,169 husbands were away from their wives, and that 8,879 wives were away from their husbands. The detached husbands of course exceeded the detached wives by 4,290 or by the same quantity which the total number of wives in the Colony exceeded the total number of husbands. [Number of husbands and wives living together and separate.]

11.

It is further evident that of every 1,000 married men in the Colony when the Census was taken, 852 were living with their wives, and 148 were apart from them. Of every 1,000 married women in Victoria, 895 were with, and 105 were separate from their husbands. [Proportions of married men and women living together and apart.]

12.

Of every 1,000 males in the Colony of all ages, 298 were husbands ; of every 1,000 females, 402 were wives. [Proportions of the married in the total population.]

13.

The proportion of husbands in every 1,000 males of the age of 15 and upwards was 425 ; the proportion of wives in every 1,000 females at the same age was 697. [Proportion of the married in the population of 15 and upwards.]

14.

Of males of 20 and upwards 458, and of females of 20 and upwards 784 in every 1,000 were married. [Proportions of the married in the population of 20 and upwards.]

15.

Six hundred and twenty-six males in 1,000 at the age of 40 and upwards were husbands, 781 females at the same period of life were wives. [Proportions of the married in the population of 40 and upwards.]

16.

Of the whole population, 1 in 3 were living in the married state ; of the population over 20 years old rather more than half were married. [Proportions of the married in whole population and in that of 20 and upwards.]

17.

Of males over 20, about 3 in 7 ; and of females over 20, about 7 in 9, were married. [Proportions of married males and females in population of 20 and upwards.]

18.

As the populations of the municipalities and of the mining districts differ from each other, and from the population of the whole of Victoria, in the relative numbers of the sexes, so also they vary in the numbers of men and women in the married state. [Differences in populations of municipalities and mining districts from population of the Colony.]

19.

Taking the population of 20 years old and upwards, 571 men in every 1,000 were husbands, in the municipalities, and 396 on the gold fields, against 458 in the Colony ; [Proportion of the married in urban and mining populations.]

737 women in 1,000, at the same age, were wives, in the municipalities, and 853 on the gold fields, against 784 in Victoria.

20.

Under the age of 15, 3 boys were returned as husbands, 7 girls as wives and 1 as a widow. Between 15 and 20, 69 youths were returned as husbands, and 5 as widowers ; at the same age, 2,077 females were returned as wives, and 25 as widows. [Married and widowed under 15 and between 15 and 20.]

21.

Assuming each wife to represent a family, there were in Victoria, when the Census was taken, 84,550 integral families ; but there were also 13,457 families in a state of dissolution, 6,623 by the death of the husband, and 6,834 by the death of the wife at their head, the former being the number of widows and the latter the number of widowers returned. [Widowers and widows.]

22.

The proportion of widowers to the male population was 1 in 44 ; that of widows to the female population was 1 in 32. [Proportion of widowers and widows to the whole population.]

23.

Of men of the age of 20 and upwards 1 in 28 was a widower ; of women at the same age 1 in 16 was a widow. [Proportion of widowers and widows in population of 20 and upwards.]

24.

The husbands were to the widowers in the proportion of 13 to 1. The wives to the widows were also in the proportion of 13 to 1. [Proportion of husbands to widowers and of wives to widows.]

25.

Up to the age of 75 there were more husbands than widowers at each quinquennial period ; after that age the widowers were in excess of the husbands. [Ages at which husbands are more numerous than widowers, and the contrary.]

26.

Under the age of 65 the wives were more numerous at each period than the widows. After that age the latter were found at each period to exceed the former. [Ages at which wives are more numerous than widows, and the contrary.]

27.

Perhaps one of the most surprising results arising from the disparity of the sexes in Victoria is that there were more widowers returned than widows, the excess of the former being 211. In countries where the sexes are equal, the excess, as is well known, is in the opposite direction, and much greater. In England and Wales, according to the latest returns, there are more than twice as many widows as widowers. [Widowers and widows in Victoria and England and Wales.]

28.

If unmarried persons of the age of 15 and upwards are to be termed bachelors and spinsters, Victoria contained, when the Census was taken, 113,350 of the former and 30,117 of the latter, or 376 bachelors to 100 spinsters. If this designation be not used until the parties have attained the age of 20, the numbers would be 98,198 bachelors and 16,128 spinsters, or 609 of the former to 100 of the latter. [Bachelors and spinsters.]

29.

If 20 and upwards for males and 15 and upwards for females be considered the marriageable ages, then the proportions would be 326 bachelors to 100 spinsters. At these ages there is an excess of bachelors in all the counties and districts, ranging from 1,900 bachelors to 100 spinsters in the Wimmera, 1,086 in Rodney, and 1,063 in Anglesey, to 137 bachelors to 100 spinsters in Normanby, 142 in Bourke, 173 in Grant, and 180 in Villiers. [Relative proportions of bachelors and spinsters in different counties.]

30.

Unmarried males at the age of 15 and upwards were in the proportion of 542 in 1,000 males of the same age. Unmarried females of 15 and upwards were in the proportion of 248 in 1,000 females at that age. [Proportion of bachelors and spinsters in population of 15 and upwards.]

31.

At the age of 20 and upwards, bachelors amounted to 507 in 1,000 of the male population ; at the same age, unmarried females amounted to 153 in 1,000 of the female population. [Proportion of bachelors and spinsters in population of 20 and upwards.]

32.

Between the ages of 20 and 40 there were 84,274 bachelors in Victoria. At the corresponding period of life there were only 15,264 spinsters returned. This gives a proportion of 552 to 100, or 5½ to 1. [Proportion of bachelors and spinsters in population between 20 and 40.]

33.

Over the age of 40 there were 13,497 men who had never been married ; over that age there were only 829 women in a like condition. [Proportion of bachelors and spinsters in population of 40 and upwards.]

34.

In municipalities, bachelors of 20 years old and upwards amounted to 392, and on the gold fields to as many as 570, in 1,000 males of the same age, against 507 in 1,000 for the whole Colony. Spinsters of 20 and upwards were in the proportion of 187 in 1,000 females of the same age in municipalities, and only 98 on the gold fields, against 153 in 1,000 for the whole of Victoria. [Proportion of bachelors and spinsters in urban and mining population.]

35.

The number of births registered during the Census year was 23,461, of which 22,965 were set down as legitimate, 496 as illegitimate. The number of married women returned between the ages of 15 and 45 was 74,568, therefore the children born in wedlock were in the proportion of 308 to every 1,000 married women at child-bearing ages. The number of single women and widows between 15 and 45 amounted to 32,815, to every 1,000 of whom 15 children were born during the year. Upon the supposition that there were as many single women living in concubinage to every illegitimate child born, as there were married women to every legitimate child born, it would follow that 1,611, or 1 in every 20, of the single women in the Colony must, during the year 1861, have lived an irregular life. [Proportion of illegitimate and illegitimate births to the wives and single women.]

36.

It may be further interesting to note, that if all the unmarried women and all the widows between the ages of 15 and 45 had been in the married state, the births during the Census year would have probably amounted to not less than 33,000, instead of to about 23,500, which in round numbers were actually recorded. [Number of births which would result if all female populatiion were married.]

I have the honor to be,

Sir,

Your most obedient Servant,

WILLIAM HENRY ARCHER,

Registrar-General.

The Honorable the Chief Secretary,

&c., &c., &c.

REPORT.

Registrar-General's Office,

Melbourne, 20th September 1864.

SIR,

I have the honor to submit the returns of the Education of the People, as compiled from the Census taken on the 7th April, 1861. [Education of the people.]

2.

These returns give an account of the numbers and ages of those persons who have acquired the rudimentary arts of reading and writing, but do not supply any particulars of the higher branches of knowledge, which many such persons also possess. The returns are, however, a most valuable addition to our statistical knowledge, presenting as they do a means of ascertaining not only the minimum amount of literary instruction existing among our adults, but also of observing to some extent the results that have accrued from past educational systems, upon which such vast sums of public money, and so large an amount of official labor have been expended. [Census enquiry of education only refers to reading and writing.]

3.

The particulars in the various tables are indicated under the following headings :— [Summary of contents of tables.]

  1. The proportions per cent. of the educated, the partially educated, and the uneducated at the last five Census Periods, those above and under 21 years of age being distinguished.

  2. The number in every 100 of the population at the various quinquennial periods of age who could read and write, read only, or who could not read at the last three Censuses.

  3. The number of persons, males and females, at each quinquennial period of age, living in Victoria, who could read and write, read only, could not read, or whose education was unknown.

  4. The number of persons, males and females, at each quinquennial period of age, living in corporate towns and municipalities, who could read and write, read only, could not read, or whose education was unknown.

  5. The number of persons, males and females, at each quinquennial period of age, living in mining districts, who could read and write, read only, or whose education was unknown.

  6. The number in every 100 of the populations of the Colony, the corporate towns and municipalities, and the mining districts, at the various quinquennial periods of age, who could read and write, read only, or who could not read.

  7. The numbers and proportions per cent. of the persons, males and females, of 5 years old and upwards, living in each county and pastoral district, who could read and write, read only, or who could not read.

  8. The numbers and proportions per cent. of persons, males and females, of 21 years old and upwards, in each electoral province, who could read and write, read only, or who could not read.

  9. The numbers and proportions per cent. of males and females, of 21 years old and upwards, in each electoral district, who could read and write, read only, or who could not read.

  10. The degree of education possessed by children between the ages of 5 and 15, of different religious denominations.

  11. The degree of education possessed by males and females, of different ages, in each county and pastoral district.

  12. The degree of education possessed by males and females, of different ages, in each electoral province.

  13. The degree of education possessed by males and females, of different ages, in each electoral district.

  14. The degree of education possessed by males and females, of different ages, in each corporate town and municipality.

  15. The degree of education possessed by males and females, of different ages, living on the gold fields in each mining district.

4.

The total population enumerated, exclusive of Chinese, aborigines and travelers, amounted to 510,552 persons. Of these, the enquiry as to education was not responded to in 3,437 instances. The population dealt with throughout these returns is, therefore, 507,115. [Numbers of the population deals with in this return.]

5.

Of this number 380,857, or about three-fourths, were able to read, and 324,228, or nearly two-thirds, were able to read and write. On the other hand, 126,258, or about a fourth, were entirely uninstructed. [Numbers able to read and write read only and unable to read.]

6.

The uneducated portion will of course be found to be much diminished, if the children under five, amounting to 90,896, are deducted from the total number. Of the residue, embracing all persons above five years of age, 38,719, or about 1 in 11, were unable to read ; 92,033, or rather more than a fifth, were unable to write. [Education possessed by persons over 5 years of age.]

7.

Of the children under 5, 87, viz., 52 boys and 35 girls, or 1 in every 1,000, were stated to be able to read and write, and 3,311 of both sexes, of 36 in every 1,000, to read and not write ; making, in all, 3,398 children under 5 who could read. [Education possessed by children under 5 years of age.]

8.

The period between 5 years of age and 15 may be called the school age. The number of children returned at that age (excluding the unspecified as to education) was 86,651 ; of these, 42,091, or nearly half could read and write, 25,411 could only read, and 19,149, or more than a fifth, were uneducated. [Education possessed by children between 5 and 15 years old.]

9.

If persons over 15 years of age be considered, those unable to write are found to have numbered 47,473, out of a total population of 329,507, or 1 in every 7. The number at the same period of life unable to read was 19,570, or 1 person in every 17. [Education possessed by persons over 15 years old.]

10.

The number of persons who had attained their legal majority of 21 years and upwards was 289,779. Of these, 42,752, or 1 in 7 could not write ; 17,856, or 1 in 16 could not read. [Education possessed by persons of 21 years and upwards.]

11.

In municipalities 81 people in every 100, over 5 years old, and on the gold fields (inclusive of gold field municipalities) 79 people in every 100 at the same age could read and write. The standard reached in towns is therefore higher than that on the gold [Standard of education in towns and on gold fields compared with that of the colony.]

fields. Both however are above the average of the whole Colony, wherein only 78 in 100 at ages above 5 years could read and write. The latter average is brought down by the low state of education in the rural districts, where the proportional numbers able to read and write are fewer than in towns or on the gold fields.

12.

A result favorable to Victoria is elicited by a comparison of these educational returns with those of the adjacent colonies of South Australia and New South Wales. Taking all persons over 5 years of age ; in Victoria 779 in every 1,000 could read and write, against 694 in South Australia and against only 639 in New South Wales. At the same age 205 in every 1,000 were unable to read in New South Wales, against 120 in 1,000 in South Australia, and against only 93 in 1,000 in Victoria. [Standard of education in Victoria superior to that in New South Wales and South Australia.]

13.

At the school age, or from 5 years old to 15, the results of South Australia are not greatly different from those of Victoria, although slightly in favor of the latter. In South Australia 760 children in 1,000 could read ; in Victoria 778 in 1,000 could read. In both Colonies 486 in 1,000 could also write. New South Wales, as regards the amount of education possessed by children at the school age, is behind both the other Colonies. Only 702 children in 1,000 could read, and no more than 439 in 1,000 could write. [Standard of children's education in Victoria equal to that in South Australia, and superior to that in New South Wales.]

14.

In Victoria the facilities for education are equally open to children of either sex, and in practice boys are not more often called away for the lighter labors of the field or the workshop than are girls to assist in household duties. The result is that up to the age of 21 nearly the same degree of education is possessed by both sexes. Relatively speaking, a few more males than females can read and write, but on the other hand the proportional number of females unable to read is not quite so great as that of males. After the age of 21, however, the number of uninstructed female immigrants arriving in the colony begins to operate upon the educational position of the female portion of the community, and from that age onwards the relative number of educated males is much greater than that of females. [Education possessed by males and females compared.]

15.

A most important return as showing the degree of success which has attended the labors of the different religious bodies in regard to primary instruction among the rising generation has been compiled in the form of Table X, which gives the number of children between 5 and 15 years of age belonging to each denomination, and the numbers of each who have attained the two first grades of literary instruction. The following are a few of the results. [Return showing degree of education possessed by children of different religious sects.]

16.

Of the three principal protestant denominations, namely, the Church of England, the Presbyterian, and the Wesleyan, the children of the last named are found to have the highest proportion of children possessing the rudiments of instruction, inasmuch as 88 Wesleyan children in 100 could read, against 82 Presbyterian children and 77 children of members of the Church of England. Fifty-seven Wesleyan children in 100 could write, against only 50 of the Presbyterians and against 47 of the Church of England. Only 12 Wesleyan children in 100 were unable to read against 18 Presbyterian children, and 23 of the Church of England. [Education possessed by children of members of Church of England, Presbyterians, and Wesleyans.]

17.

The standard of the Independents and Baptists, as regards their children's primary instruction is higher even than that of the Wesleyans. The returns show that no less than 88 children of Independents and 87 of Baptists in every 100 could read, and that 61 in 100 of Independents and 60 of Baptists could write. [Education possessed by children of Independents and Baptists.]

18.

Of Roman Catholic children the returns show only 69 in 100 as being able to read, and no more than 41 in 100 as being able to write, whilst as many as 31 in 100 were uneducated. This is the least satisfactory result shown by the educational returns of any religious denomination. [Education possessed by children of Roman Catholics.]

19.

The returns relating to the education of the children of our Jewish fellow colonists show that much care has been expended upon their early education, seeing that [Education possessed by children of Jews.]

63 in 100 between 5 and 15 years of age could read and write, being a higher proportion than was found to obtain in any of the bodies I have previously named.

20.

Before concluding this report it may be well to state, that the number of children at school, according to the occupation returns of the Census, was 52,366.

*

This number is less than the numbers upon the books of the various schools during the same year, which, in the "Statistics of Victoria," for 1861, were given as follows :— [Number of Children receiving school education.]

No. of Scholars on the Rolls.
Denominational schools37,476
National schools13,869
Private schools5,128
Total56,473

21.

The discrepancy between the Census return and the return furnished by the various school authorities is probably owing to the former giving theactual attendanceof scholars, which it is well known is always somewhat less than the number shown upon the school rolls. [Discrepancy between census returns and those of school authorities accounted for.]

22.

The Census return, understood to be that of children actually attending school, would give the number of scholars as 1 in 10 of the population, exclusive of Chinese and Aborigines, or as 43 per cent. of the children between the ages of 3 and 15. The school return, showing the number on the rolls, would give a proportion of scholars equal to 1 in 9 of the population of all ages, or of 47 per cent. of the population between 3 and 15 years of age. [Proportion of scholars to the population.]

I have the honor to be,

Sir,

Your most obedient Servant,

WILLIAM HENRY ARCHER,

Registrar-General.

The Honorable the Chief Secretary,

Melbourne.

REPORT.

REPORT.

Registrar-General's Office,

Melbourne, 5th October, 1864.

SIR,

I have the honor to present herewith the " Health of the People," being the eighth and last part of the returns compiled from the Census taken on the 7th April, 1861. [Health of the people.]

2.

This return, which, in the absence of a better term, I have thus designated, shows the numbers and ages of persons unable to perform their usual avocations on account of sickness or accidents, of lunatics, of deaf and dumb persons, and of the blind. The enquiry into these various particulars was instituted for the first time in Victoria in the Census under notice. [Nature of the enquiry.]

The following results will be found in the various tables :—

  1. The total number of sick persons of both sexes, of lunatics, of those suffering from accidents, of the deaf and dumb, and of the blind, and the numbers of each to every 10,000 of the population. [Summary of the contents of tables.]

  2. The number and ages of sick persons of both sexes, of lunatics, of those suffering from accidents, of the deaf and dumb, and of the blind, in the Colony of Victoria.

  3. The number and ages of sick persons of both sexes in each county and pastoral district.

  4. The number and ages of persons of both sexes suffering from accidents in each county and pastoral district.

  5. The number and ages of deaf and dumb persons of both sexes in each county and pastoral district.

  6. The number and ages of blind persons of both sexes in each county and pastoral district.

3.

The total number of cases of infirmity, including the sick, the maimed, the insane, the deaf and dumb, and the blind, amounted to 3,745 ; which, upon a population of 540,322, gives a proportion of 1 person in every 145 rendered non-effective, either temporarily or permanently, by one of the causes adduced. The disabled males numbered 3,112, or 1 in every 106 of the male population ; the disabled females numbered 633, or 1 in every 334 of the female population of the colony. [Number of non-effectives and proportion to the population.]

4.

The sick amounted to 2,343, or 1 in every 231 of the population ; males contributed 2,045, females 298, to this number. Those suffering from accidents numbered 556, or 1 maimed person in every 971 of the population ; of these, only 11 were females. The sick and the maimed, taken together, amount in the aggregate to 2,899, a number which furnishes a proportion relatively to the whole population of 1 in 186. Of the sick 1,485, and of the maimed 130, were inmates of hospitals at the period of the Census. [Sick and maimed.]

5.

The lunatics given in these returns are only those in the Yarra Bend Asylum. If lunatics existed elsewhere, which was probably the case to a small extent, especially in some of the gaols, they could not be traced in the schedules. The number returned was 660, viz., 397 males and 263 females. This gives a proportion of 1 lunatic to every 819 inhabitants of the colony,—1 lunatic male to every 828 males, 1 lunatic female to every 805 females. [Lunatics]

6.

The deaf and dumb returned amounted to 60, viz:—37 males, and 23 females. Those numbers in proportion to the population of the colony, give 1 deaf mute in every 9,005 persons of both sexes, 1 deaf and dumb male in every 8,882 males, 1 deaf and dumb female in every 9,203 females. [Deaf and Dumb.]

7.

The blind numbered 126, or 1 blind person in every 4,288 of both sexes. Of the blind, 88 were males, or 1 in every 3,735 males in the colony ; 38 were females, or 1 in every 5,570 females. [Blind.]

8.

Since Victoria is indebted to immigration for three-fourths of her population, and persons afflicted with deaf muteism or blindness would not be likely to become immigrants, it would obviously be unfair to compare the statistics of these maladies as they exist in this colony with those of older countries, in all of which the proportional number of deaf and dumb and of blind persons is much higher than it is with us.

*

In some parts of Switzerland there is said to be 1 deaf mute in every 206 of the population. In England and Wales, according to the latest returns, the proportion is 1 in 1,738. The statistics relating to blindness show a range varying from 1 blind person in 482 of the inhabitants of Norway, to 1 in 979 of those of England and Wales.—(Report of the Census of Great Britain, 1851.)

The results obtained however also contrast favorably with those of South Australia, which is the only other colony of this group which appears to have published returns similar to these. In South Australia there is 1 deaf mute in as few as 6,341 persons ; in Victoria there is only 1 in 9,005. In South Australia there is 1 blind person in every 3,252 inhabitants against 1 in 4,288 in Victoria. [Statistics of blindness and deaf dumbness in Victoria and South Australia compared.]

9.

The ages of the sick and infirm are given in the tables, in quinquennial periods ; by grouping these periods the following results are obtained :— [Ages of sick and infirm.]

10.

Seven per cent. of the sick and 9 per cent. of the maimed were under 20 years of age ; but less than 2 per cent. of the lunatics. As many as 55 per cent. of the deaf and dumb and 21 per cent. of the blind were under 20 years old. [Under 20.]

11.

At the period between 20 and 40 are found 53 per cent. of the sick ; 64 per cent. of the lunatics ; 60 per cent. of the crippled ; 27 per cent. of the deaf and dumb, and 29 per cent. of the blind. [20 to 40.]

12.

The next vicennial period, from 40 to 60, contains 30 per cent. of the sick ; 30 per cent. of the lunatics ; 26 per cent. of those suffering from accidents ; 13 per cent. of the deaf and dumb, and 33 per cent. of the blind. [40 to 60.]

13.

The period between 60 and 80 embraces 10 per cent. of the sick, less than 2 per cent. of the lunatics ; 5 per cent. of the maimed ; 5 per cent. of the deaf and dumb, and as many as 16 per cent. of the blind. [60 to 80.]

14.

Twelve sick and 2 blind persons were returned as being upwards of 80 years of age. [Upwards of 80.]

15.

It may be interesting to note, that 1 person, a male, was returned as deaf and dumb and blind, and that 2 of the deaf and dumb, 1 male and 1 female, were returned as idiots, also that 1 Chinese was returned as deaf and dumb, and 3 Aborigines as blind. [Idiots, Chinese, Aborigines, &c.]

16.

Before bringing to a close this last Report upon the subject of the Census, I feel it is only due to myself again to place on record what I have several times stated in the course of the Reports upon the various Parts, viz., that the returns were all ready for the press before the end of 1862, and that the delay in their publication since that period has arisen from circumstances entirely outside this Department, and consequently beyond my own control. [Delay in publishing the returns alluted to.]

17.

In conclusion, I feel it due to the officers of the Statistic Branch of this Department to record my approbation of the assiduity and fidelity with which they have respectively discharged their various duties from time to time in relation to the Census. And in so doing I also beg to make special mention of the services of Mr. H. H. Hayter, the senior statistic clerk of this Department, who has rendered me at all times zealous and efficient assistance, not only in the preparation of this and previous reports, but in the supervision and compilation of all the tables. [Conclusion.]

I have the honor to be,

Sir,

Your most obedient Servant,

WILLIAM HENRY ARCHER,

Registrar-General.

The Honorable the Chief Secretary.

NOTE.—Of the Sick, 1,485 persons, viz., 1,015 males, and 470 females, were patients in public hospitals. The Lunatics were all in the Yarra Bend Lunatic Asylum. If any existed elsewhere they could not be traced in the schedules. Of those suffering from Accidents, 130 persons, viz., 125 males and 5 females, were in hospitals. In the second part of the Census. " The Occupations," the numbers of the Deaf and Dumb, and of the Blind, were set down in the aggregate as 204, viz., 141 males and 63 females. A subsequent and more careful investigation of the schedules has however revealed the fact that 18 of those which were tabulated for that return as Deaf and Dumb, viz., 16 males and 2 females, were only returned by the householders as deaf. These have, therefore, been excluded from this and the following Tables.
